      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1784580782150,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "I solved it using kadane's algorithm\non the deltas",
      "fontSize": 124,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "I solved it using kadane's algorithm\non the deltas",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "T7FyaHFYKeAsdzCyLzEk8",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 3900.136561814498,
      "y": 55.316729159974784,
      "width": 16911.3125,
      "height": 465,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#2f9e44",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "hachure",
      "strokeWidth": 4,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 2,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b3F",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 398337894,
      "version": 901,
      "versionNonce": 1421043514,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1784581385918,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "3. A third Greedy approach as pointed out by Gemini after i successfully solved the problem is that we could have just in a single pass maintained the lowest stock price encountered. and the maximumProfit as well. and whenever we encounter a lower stock price\nthan our current minimum we change our current minimum and we keep comparing new stock prices against this minimum and if the difference between the current stock price and our minimum is greater than our maximum profit we update our maximum profit as well and this approach\nwhich is quite similar to our kadane's approach also solves this in a single pass. i guess this was my learning from the question. but i am glad i solved it myself yipeeee.",
      "fontSize": 124,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "3. A third Greedy approach as pointed out by Gemini after i successfully solved the problem is that we could have just in a single pass maintained the lowest stock price encountered. and the maximumProfit as well. and whenever we encounter a lower stock price\nthan our current minimum we change our current minimum and we keep comparing new stock prices against this minimum and if the difference between the current stock price and our minimum is greater than our maximum profit we update our maximum profit as well and this approach\nwhich is quite similar to our kadane's approach also solves this in a single pass. i guess this was my learning from the question. but i am glad i solved it myself yipeeee.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    }
